{
  "root_cause": "The IPC pool handle cache was disabled, so concurrent multimodal reconstructions could repeatedly open and release the same imported CUDA/HIP IPC pool allocation. The sender can recycle a feature slice (or release a non-retained backing allocation) before another TP scheduler has reconstructed it; without a receiver-held cached storage keeping the imported pool mapping alive, the serialized handle can therefore refer to freed/recycled device memory and _new_shared_cuda opens a stale device pointer.",
  "fix": "Set SGLANG_USE_IPC_POOL_HANDLE_CACHE=1 in launch_qwen3.5_27b_sglang.sh, while keeping SGLANG_USE_CUDA_IPC_TRANSPORT=1.",
  "evidence": "crash_qwen3.5-27b-mmmu-con128.log:3614: '[TP1] Failed to deserialize from CUDA IPC handle (HIP error: invalid device pointer'; lines 3645-3647 show reconstruct_on_target_device -> torch.UntypedStorage._new_shared_cuda raising torch.AcceleratorError: HIP error: invalid device pointer; line 3654 says 'SIGQUIT received... It usually means one child failed.'"
}

